{
  "id": "145586a0-b700-4d3b-8ddc-9addb1559651",
  "slug": "cre-insurance-certificate-compliance-check",
  "name": "CRE Insurance Certificate Compliance Review",
  "summary": "This skill guides an LLM through a contract-driven, endorsement-focused review of CRE insurance certificates (typically ACORD 25) to confirm compliance with an Access Agreement's coverage limits, Additional Insured requirements, primary/non-contributory status, and waiver of subrogation provisions. It emphasizes converting the agreement's insurance clause into verifiable requirements, treating COIs as non-binding indicators rather than proof of coverage, and demanding endorsement-level documentary evidence for all critical terms. The skill produces a defensible compliance determination with broker-ready deficiency instructions and escalation guidance, and embeds ethical, privilege, malpractice-prevention, and anti-hallucination guardrails throughout.",
  "content": "# CRE Insurance Certificate Compliance Review\n\n## 1. Opening Context\n\nThis skill produces a lawyer-grade compliance review of insurance certificates (typically ACORD 25 Certificates of Liability Insurance) and related policy endorsement evidence against the insurance and risk-transfer requirements in a commercial real estate (\"CRE\") Access Agreement (or similar site access, entry, license, or services agreement). In practice, these reviews are often the only gatekeeping mechanism before an owner, property manager, lender's consultant, contractor, vendor, or other \"Recipient\" is permitted on-site. Done well, the review reduces the client's loss exposure by confirming that the required coverages and limits are actually in place, the client is properly protected as an Additional Insured where required, and coverage will respond first and without erosion by the client's own insurance when \"primary and non-contributory\" status is required.\n\nExecution of this work product requires a high degree of precision because insurance deficiencies often remain hidden until a loss occurs. A certificate is merely a snapshot of coverage; it is not the policy itself, and in most jurisdictions it does not grant rights to the certificate holder. If an attorney or paralegal fails to identify that a certificate lacks an endorsement establishing Additional Insured status, omits required \"Primary and Non-Contributory\" language, or misses a \"Waiver of Subrogation\" gap, the client may find its own insurance program responding to a claim that should have been covered by the Recipient. A competent review ensures that risk is properly shifted to the party performing the work or accessing the property, preserving the client's loss history and policy limits. Good execution looks like a disciplined comparison of the Access Agreement's insurance clause to what the Recipient has actually produced, a clear written deficiency notice identifying exactly what must be corrected, and a risk-based escalation when the documentation cannot prove compliance.\n\n## 2. Understanding the Context and Purpose\n\nIn CRE operations, an Access Agreement shifts or allocates risk among the property-side parties (owner, landlord, lender, property manager, asset manager) and the accessing party (contractor, engineer, environmental consultant, broker, tenant contractor, telecom vendor, etc.). The insurance requirements are typically paired with indemnity obligations: the Recipient promises to defend and indemnify certain \"Indemnitees,\" and insurance is intended to fund that promise and reduce coverage disputes.\n\nThe attorney's role is to ensure the \"Insurance\" section of the Agreement is not just boilerplate but an enforceable shield. You are looking for a precise match between the contractual requirement and the evidence of coverage. You must approach this with an adversarial mindset: assume the insurance carrier will look for any technicality to deny coverage to your client as an Additional Insured after a loss. Your goal is to close those technical loopholes before the first person steps onto the property.\n\nThe primary audience for the review output is the client's transaction or asset-management team, the property manager or site operations team, and sometimes the counterparty's risk manager or broker. Their expectations are pragmatic: a pass/fail conclusion, a short explanation of what is missing, and specific instructions that a broker can implement. Strategically, read the insurance clause as part of an integrated risk-transfer package: the Additional Insured requirement is only meaningful if it tracks the contract's indemnity scope; primary/non-contributory language matters most when multiple parties have overlapping policies; and waiver of subrogation is most valuable when the parties want to avoid insurer-versus-insurer litigation.\n\nScope boundary: this skill is designed for contract-driven certificate compliance reviews in CRE access and vendor contexts. It does not replace a full policy review, does not opine on the enforceability of indemnity provisions, and does not provide coverage opinions. Where a coverage position turns on policy wording, manuscript endorsements, or state-specific insurance law, the skill instructs the executing LLM to escalate and flag items for attorney verification.\n\n## 3. Prerequisites and Information Gathering\n\nBefore beginning the substantive review, the following documents and data points must be obtained and organized. Do not proceed to a final compliance determination until these materials are available, as a partial review often leads to critical omissions.\n\nAt minimum, collect: (a) the executed Access Agreement (or the signature-ready final) including all exhibits, insurance schedules, and any insurance requirements rider or property rules incorporated by reference; (b) every certificate of insurance (COI) provided (typically ACORD 25 for CGL, and sometimes separate ACORD forms for auto, workers' compensation, umbrella/excess, professional liability, pollution legal liability, or builder's risk); (c) copies of Additional Insured endorsements (e.g., ISO Forms CG 20 10 and CG 20 37) and any primary/non-contributory endorsements if provided; (d) any waiver of subrogation endorsements if required; (e) the Recipient's insurer and broker contact details; and (f) the project or work description and dates and locations covered by the access.\n\nThe first set of clarifying questions should confirm: who exactly must be named as Additional Insured (the full legal names of the owner, property manager, lender, and their respective affiliates, subsidiaries, partners, members, managers, officers, directors, employees, and agents as listed in the agreement); whether the contract requires completed operations coverage; whether there is any requirement for specific ISO endorsement forms; whether the work involves heightened risks (hot work, roofing, structural modification, environmental sampling, confined space) that may implicate exclusions; and whether access is contingent on proof of insurance \"acceptable to\" the client.\n\nIf any required document is missing\u2014endorsements are required but not provided, an umbrella is required but no umbrella COI is provided, or policy numbers are omitted\u2014the LLM must pause and request the missing inputs before issuing a final compliance determination. The LLM should prompt the user: \"I have identified that [Missing Document] is not provided. To perform a competent legal review, I require this document to verify that the language on the certificate is actually supported by the underlying policy. Should I proceed with a preliminary review based only on the COI, or would you like to provide the missing files?\" If the user insists on proceeding, the LLM may produce a preliminary risk memo that clearly labels every conclusion as conditional and identifies what cannot be verified.\n\n## 4. Step-by-Step Process\n\n### Step 1: Parse and Normalize the Access Agreement Insurance Requirements into a Verification Matrix\n\nStart by extracting the insurance clause(s) from the Access Agreement and turning them into a normalized set of requirements that can be tested against the COI and endorsements. Insurance provisions often contain nested conditions\u2014limits, form requirements, Additional Insured status, primary wording, notice obligations, deductible constraints, carrier rating constraints, and special coverages\u2014that cannot be reliably checked if you treat the clause as prose. Translate the clause into objective verification questions.\n\nExecute this step by reading the agreement for: required lines of coverage (CGL, auto, workers' compensation/employers' liability, umbrella/excess, professional, pollution, cyber, etc.); required minimum limits (per occurrence, aggregate, products/completed operations aggregate, personal and advertising injury, fire damage, medical payments, combined single limit for auto); how limits must apply (e.g., \"per project\" or \"per location\" aggregate versus policy-level aggregate); Additional Insured scope and the exact entities that must be covered; primary and non-contributory language; waiver of subrogation; cancellation and non-renewal notice; required insurer rating (often \"A- VII or better\" from AM Best); and any requirement that coverage be written on an occurrence form and include contractual liability.\n\nWhere the clause references specific endorsement forms or ISO numbers, treat those as mandatory unless the clause allows \"equivalent.\" If the clause uses ambiguous phrases like \"as required by Owner,\" flag them as discretionary and recommend attorney or client confirmation of the standard. A normalized requirement statement, for illustrative purposes, might read: \"Recipient shall maintain Commercial General Liability insurance written on an occurrence form with limits not less than $1,000,000 each occurrence and $2,000,000 general aggregate and products-completed operations aggregate. Owner, Property Manager, and Lender shall be included as Additional Insureds on a primary and non-contributory basis for ongoing and completed operations, using ISO CG 20 10 04 13 and CG 20 37 04 13 or equivalents.\"\n\nCommon mistakes to avoid include missing that the contract requires completed operations AI (many COIs only show \"additional insured\" generally), ignoring aggregate requirements, assuming umbrella \"follows form\" without proof, and failing to capture that certain parties such as a lender or property manager must be specifically named. After a claim, the Additional Insured carrier will ask whether the endorsement's AI grant matches the contract's requirement (\"as required by written contract\") and whether the named AI matches the claimant entity. If you do not normalize entity names and roles up front, you risk a mismatch\u2014for example, the certificate lists \"ABC Property Management\" but the contract requires \"ABC Property Management, LLC\" and its parent.\n\n### Step 2: Review the ACORD 25 Form for Internal Consistency and Baseline Sufficiency\n\nConduct a disciplined read of each ACORD 25. The purpose is twofold: identify obvious non-compliance quickly (missing coverage line, wrong limits, expired policy) and detect red flags suggesting the COI is unreliable or the broker is not tracking the contract requirements. Importantly, never treat the COI as proof of coverage; it is an informational snapshot only.\n\nStart with the header and policyholder/producer fields. Confirm the \"Named Insured\" matches the Recipient entity in the agreement (exact legal name and entity suffix). A common error in CRE practice is for a contractor to provide a COI in the name of a parent company or a related LLC that is not the actual signatory to the Agreement; this creates a privity gap that carriers exploit to deny coverage. Confirm the producer/broker contact information is present and usable. Then check the policy effective and expiration dates. Coverage must be in force for the entire access period; if access is ongoing, require renewal certificates in advance and build a calendar reminder. If the agreement requires that coverage be \"maintained during access and for X years thereafter\" (often for completed operations), note that a COI cannot prove future maintenance; you can only confirm current coverage and impose a contractual obligation and tracking mechanism.\n\nThen review each relevant coverage box. For Commercial General Liability, verify the occurrence limits and aggregates match the contract and that the CGL is listed as \"Occurrence\" rather than \"Claims-Made\" if the contract requires occurrence form. CRE access should almost never be on a claims-made basis, as this requires the policy to remain in effect long after the work is done to cover a later-filed claim. Confirm that \"General Aggregate\" and \"Products-Comp/Op Agg\" are shown and meet required amounts. Check the \"Limits Apply Per\" field: if the Agreement requires \"Per Project\" or \"Per Location\" aggregates, the COI must reflect this. If it is checked at the \"Policy\" level, the Recipient's aggregate limits could be exhausted by claims at completely different properties, leaving your client unprotected. For umbrella/excess, confirm it exists, confirm limits, and check whether it is \"Excess\" or \"Umbrella.\" If the contract requires it to be \"following form\" or to apply to AI coverage, the COI alone will not prove it; request the umbrella declarations and endorsement showing AI status. For auto, confirm \"Any Auto\" or the required coverage symbols, and check the combined single limit. For workers' compensation/employers' liability, confirm statutory WC and EL limits (typically at least $500,000 to $1,000,000 each for EL Each Accident, EL Disease-EA Employee, and EL Disease-Policy Limit). If the Recipient is a small firm, check if any proprietors, partners, or executive officers are excluded; if the person actually performing the work is an excluded officer, the client has a significant exposure gap. If the Recipient claims exemption from workers' compensation, treat that as non-compliant unless the contract allows it and the client accepts the risk; request proof of exemption and consider requiring an alternate risk transfer.\n\nCommon mistakes include treating \"Certificate Holder\" as equivalent to \"Additional Insured\" (it is not\u2014simply being a certificate holder does not grant insured status), relying on the \"Description of Operations\" box as definitive proof of AI status, ignoring policy dates, and overlooking that the COI may list limits that do not match the policy.\n\n### Step 3: Confirm Additional Insured Status with Endorsement-Level Evidence\n\nThe central substantive task is verifying that the client and any other required parties are actually Additional Insureds under the Recipient's CGL policy and, if required, under the umbrella/excess policy. A COI commonly checks an \"ADD'L INSRD\" box or includes narrative text in the Description of Operations, but that rarely proves the policy has a compliant endorsement or that the endorsement grants the required scope of coverage.\n\nBegin by identifying exactly who must be Additional Insured. If the agreement requires multiple entities, confirm the exact legal names, including entity suffixes, and whether the agreement extends AI to \"their respective affiliates.\" If the Recipient's policy uses a blanket Additional Insured endorsement (\"when required by written contract\"), then compliance depends on there being a written contract in place, the contract requiring AI, and the person or entity seeking AI coverage falling within the endorsement's definition. Request a copy of the blanket endorsement form and read its grant language. If the endorsement is scheduled (specific names listed), insist that the schedule include the correct entities.\n\nThen match the endorsement scope to the Access Agreement's scope. Many agreements require AI for both ongoing operations and completed operations. In standard ISO practice, ISO Form CG 20 10 addresses Additional Insured status for ongoing operations, while ISO Form CG 20 37 addresses completed operations. If the policy provides only ongoing operations AI, it may fail to cover post-completion claims such as property damage discovered after work is finished. If the agreement requires completed operations, request the endorsement that clearly extends AI status to completed operations, and confirm that the products-completed operations aggregate is present at required limits. Also check whether the AI coverage is limited to vicarious liability or extends to losses \"caused, in whole or in part\" by the named insured's acts or omissions; the scope varies by endorsement edition. Quote the endorsement's operative language in your review and flag any narrowing that could conflict with the agreement's intended risk transfer.\n\nIllustrative deficiency notice language (adapt as needed): \"The COI indicates Additional Insured status; however, the Access Agreement requires Owner, Manager, and Lender to be Additional Insureds for ongoing and completed operations. Please provide copies of the Additional Insured endorsement(s) (e.g., ISO CG 20 10 and CG 20 37, or equivalents) confirming AI status for both ongoing and completed operations, and confirming that the AI applies to the entities listed in Section __ of the Access Agreement. A certificate alone is not sufficient.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include accepting AI status without endorsements, failing to check completed operations, ignoring entity-name mismatches, and overlooking that AI endorsements may be limited to certain locations or operations that do not include the premises or the described work.\n\n### Step 4: Verify \"Primary and Non-Contributory\" Status\n\nIf the Access Agreement requires coverage to be \"primary and non-contributory,\" treat this as a separate requirement from AI status. This language ensures that if a claim arises, the Recipient's insurance pays first, and the client's own insurance does not have to contribute until the Recipient's limits are exhausted. Even when the client is an Additional Insured, the policy may still apply on an excess basis absent an endorsement or clear policy wording, particularly where \"other insurance\" clauses conflict.\n\nExecute this step by first locating the contractual requirement and then checking whether the COI's narrative includes explicit \"primary and non-contributory\" wording. Do not stop there. Because COI wording is not binding, request the actual endorsement or policy provision that establishes primary and non-contributory status for Additional Insureds. Many carriers offer a standalone primary and non-contributory endorsement; some blanket AI endorsements include primary language when required by contract. Your task is to confirm, with documentary support, that the policy will respond first for claims arising from the Recipient's work.\n\nWhen reviewing the endorsement, focus on whether the primary status is conditioned on there being a written contract requiring it, whether it applies only to ongoing operations, whether it is limited to \"that part of the premises\" used by the named insured, and whether it is overridden by any \"other insurance\" clause in the umbrella. Without a primary and non-contributory endorsement, the client's insurer may be forced to contribute or defend, leading to deductible spend and premium impacts.\n\nIllustrative internal analysis language: \"Access Agreement requires AI on PNC basis. COI contains narrative 'Owner is AI; coverage primary/non-contributory.' No PNC endorsement provided. Request endorsement or policy language confirming PNC for AI when required by written contract; otherwise treat as non-compliant.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include assuming AI status automatically means primary, ignoring that the umbrella may not be primary even if the CGL is, and not advising the client that primary and non-contributory status is most important when the client has a claim history and wants to avoid erosion of its loss runs.\n\n### Step 5: Confirm Waiver of Subrogation, Limits Structure, Umbrella Alignment, and Ancillary Requirements\n\nBeyond AI and PNC, the next frequent failure modes involve waiver of subrogation, limits that look adequate on paper but do not satisfy the contract's structure, and ancillary requirements such as carrier rating and cancellation notice.\n\nWaiver of subrogation prevents the Recipient's insurance company from suing your client to recover the money it paid on a claim. If the agreement requires it, verify via endorsement on all relevant lines (CGL, WC, auto, property). COIs sometimes indicate \"waiver of subrogation\" in a column check or narrative, but do not attach endorsements. Require the actual endorsements, especially for workers' compensation where a waiver often requires a specific form.\n\nFor limits, confirm the per-occurrence limit, general aggregate, and products-completed operations aggregate. If the agreement requires higher limits via umbrella, verify that the umbrella limit combined with underlying limits equals or exceeds the contractual requirement. If the agreement requires that the umbrella apply to CGL, auto, and employer's liability, request proof of the underlying schedule and confirm the umbrella is not limited to fewer lines. If the umbrella does not recognize AI status, the client may only have AI coverage up to the CGL limit, which is a structural gap your review must identify before access is granted.\n\nFor insurer qualifications, if the agreement requires a minimum AM Best rating (e.g., A- VII), the COI may list insurer NAIC numbers but not the rating. Request evidence of rating such as a broker attestation or AM Best confirmation, and note that ratings can change; consider a process for re-verification on renewal.\n\nFor cancellation and notice, many agreements require the Recipient to provide advance notice of cancellation or material change. The ACORD 25 includes standard disclaimer language that it \"confers no rights\" and that notice is not guaranteed. Most modern ACORD forms have deleted the \"will endeavor to mail\" language. Treat any contract requirement that the insurer provide notice directly to the client as difficult to enforce via COI alone; require the Recipient to covenant to provide notice and to request the insurer or broker add a notice endorsement where available. Flag this as a risk if the client is relying on notice for access control.\n\nFor deductibles and self-insured retentions, if the agreement caps them, a COI usually will not show them reliably. Request declarations or a broker letter stating the deductible and SIR amounts. If there is a large SIR, advise the client about credit risk: the Recipient may effectively be self-insuring the first layer, and the AI may face delayed defense or indemnity while the Recipient funds the retention.\n\nCommon mistakes include ignoring the products-completed ops aggregate, failing to confirm the umbrella attaches over AI coverage, overlooking waiver of subrogation as optional when it is a bargained-for term, and neglecting to check the \"Description of Operations\" box for suspicious language like \"Excluding Residential Work\" or geographic exclusions that could invalidate coverage for the specific project.\n\n### Step 6: Produce a Clear Written Compliance Determination, Deficiency Notice, and Escalation Recommendation\n\nYour output should be a concise, professional memo or email-ready report that states whether the submission is compliant, non-compliant, or conditionally compliant pending documentation; lists each requirement and the corresponding evidence; and provides broker-ready corrective instructions. The review itself is part of the client's risk control record: it shows diligence, supports denying access if necessary, and creates a paper trail that the Recipient was notified of deficiencies.\n\nStructure the output so that a non-lawyer operations team can act on it. Use plain language but be precise about what needs to be provided\u2014for example, \"provide AI endorsement showing completed operations\" rather than \"fix additional insured.\" Where the issue is a name mismatch, write the exact name to use. Where the issue is missing limits, state the required limit and the currently evidenced limit.\n\nIllustrative \"conditional approval\" language (adapt as needed): \"Conditional approval for site access is not recommended until the items below are provided and confirmed. If the business team elects to allow access notwithstanding, document that decision as an exception to policy and confirm whether additional supervision, restricted scope, or other mitigations apply.\"\n\nInclude an escalation recommendation when the Recipient cannot produce endorsements, when endorsement language appears materially narrower than the contract requirement, when the carrier rating is below the contractual minimum, when the work presents heightened risk, or when the agreement's insurance terms are internally inconsistent or unusually aggressive. Escalation can be to in-house counsel, outside coverage counsel, or the client's risk manager depending on the organization.\n\nAdversarial awareness for the written record: your review may be discoverable in later litigation. Avoid speculative statements about coverage or fault. Stick to contract requirements and documentary evidence. If you must explain risk, frame it as \"unable to verify\" rather than \"coverage will be denied.\"\n\n## 5. Critical Legal Standards and Compliance\n\nCompetence and diligence require that the reviewer understand the limits of certificates and avoid overstatements. Under Model Rule 1.1 (Competence), the lawyer\u2014and by extension an LLM operating under attorney supervision\u2014must perform a reasonable review proportional to the risk. In this context, competence includes understanding that a COI is not a policy and that specific endorsements are required to bind a carrier. Under Model Rule 1.3 (Diligence), the reviewer must not treat a COI as conclusive proof where the contract requires endorsements or where material terms cannot be verified. Under Model Rule 1.4 (Communication), the lawyer must explain constraints and risks to the client in a way that permits informed decisions, particularly when the business team wants to grant access despite deficiencies. Never instruct a client that they are \"fully covered\" based solely on a COI; always qualify the analysis by stating that coverage is subject to the actual terms and conditions of the underlying insurance policies.\n\nWhen communicating with third parties such as the Recipient's broker, Model Rule 4.1 requires truthfulness. When a submission is deficient, the deficiency notice should describe the gap and request specific documents rather than asserting that the Recipient is uninsured.\n\nConfidentiality and privilege require treating the Access Agreement, insurance materials, and internal review notes as client confidential under Model Rule 1.6. If the review is conducted at counsel's direction for legal advice, communications may be privileged; but sharing the analysis broadly\u2014for example, forwarding to third-party property managers not within the scope of privilege\u2014can waive privilege. The skill should instruct the LLM to ask who the client is, who will receive the output, and whether the output should be labeled \"Privileged and Confidential / Attorney-Client Communication\" (while recognizing that labeling alone is not determinative; confirm privilege posture with supervising attorney).\n\nMalpractice risk concentrates in three areas: false positives (approving non-compliant insurance), name or entity mismatches that defeat AI coverage, and failure to request endorsements when the COI cannot establish compliance. Mitigation includes requiring documentary proof, using conditional language when proof is absent, and escalating uncertainties. In high-risk jurisdictions where property owners face strict liability exposure\u2014such as New York's Labor Law Sections 240 and 241 (the \"Scaffold Law\") for gravity-related construction injuries\u2014failing to verify the absence of exclusions such as \"Action Over\" or \"Labor Law\" exclusions on the Recipient's policy can expose the client to multi-million dollar uninsured losses. These high-stakes reviews must be escalated to experienced coverage counsel.\n\nAnti-indemnity statutes in multiple states can limit the enforceability of Additional Insured provisions in construction-related contexts. For example, Texas Insurance Code Chapter 151 restricts indemnification in construction contracts for certain types of negligence, and California Civil Code Section 2782 limits risk-shifting for a property owner's \"active negligence\" in construction settings. When the access activity resembles construction or improvements to real property, flag the potential impact of these statutes for attorney review, as the insurance carrier may refuse to honor Additional Insured status that violates state law.\n\n## 6. Quality Control and Review\n\nA high-quality output must accurately restate the Access Agreement's insurance requirements, accurately describe what the COI and endorsements show, and clearly distinguish between \"confirmed,\" \"indicated but not verified,\" and \"not shown/non-compliant.\" Review the analysis by re-checking each factual statement against the document, including names, policy numbers, dates, and limits.\n\nBefore finalizing, run the output through these substantive checks. Does the name of the Additional Insured exactly match the name in the Agreement, including entity suffix? Has the LLM checked for the presence of actual endorsement documents, and if only the COI is provided, has the LLM included a disclaimer that the COI is for informational purposes only and does not amend the policy? Do the combined GL and Umbrella limits meet the total limit required by the contract? Does the COI or Agreement address cancellation notice, and has the LLM flagged the ACORD 25's standard limitation on notice? Does the \"Description of Operations\" box contain any suspicious exclusionary language that could invalidate coverage?\n\nEvaluate whether the output would withstand scrutiny from an experienced risk manager or opposing counsel after a claim. If the client tenders a claim, will the tender package include the endorsements demanded during this review? If the reviewer approved without endorsements, can the decision be justified under the client's standards? If an entity name differs by punctuation or suffix, was it addressed?\n\nCitations and authority: this skill references Model Rules as generally adopted. If the output will be used in a jurisdiction with variations, flag that and require attorney confirmation. Do not provide case citations about certificate legal effect unless verified by web search at the time of execution; if the user requests such citations, the LLM must either perform web verification and provide URLs, or clearly mark the citation as requiring attorney verification.\n\nEvery deliverable must include an explicit attorney-review requirement: this output is a draft risk-control assessment that requires review by a licensed attorney or qualified risk professional before being relied upon. It does not constitute a legal opinion on the sufficiency of coverage, and all insurance determinations should be confirmed with the client's insurance broker or risk management department.\n\n## 7. Jurisdiction-Specific Adaptations\n\nThis skill is intentionally contract-driven and usable across U.S. jurisdictions because it compares submitted insurance evidence to negotiated requirements. The points that most commonly require jurisdiction-specific adaptation are the enforceability and scope of additional insured and indemnity requirements in construction-related contexts, the legal effect of certificates of insurance and potential liability of brokers for misstatements, and statutory notice-of-cancellation requirements and whether an insurer can be obligated to give notice to third parties.\n\nWhen the matter is high-risk (large limits, hazardous work, public projects, or known claim history), the skill should adapt by requiring endorsement-level proof as a hard rule and by flagging state-law constraints for attorney verification. Key jurisdiction-specific considerations include:\n\nIn New York, pay extreme attention to the Description of Operations and the endorsement language. New York's Labor Law Sections 240 and 241 create strict liability for property owners for gravity-related injuries on construction sites. Look for any exclusion regarding \"Labor Law,\" \"Heights,\" or \"Action Over\" in the policy materials; these exclusions are common and devastating to property owners. Reference: NY Insurance Law \u00a7 3426 addresses cancellation and non-renewal requirements that may also apply.\n\nIn Texas, the Anti-Indemnity Act (Texas Insurance Code Chapter 151) applies to most construction-related contracts and may limit the enforceability of Additional Insured requirements that attempt to shift liability for the indemnitee's own negligence. Verify whether the Access Agreement involves \"construction, alteration, or repair\" triggering this statute.\n\nIn California, Civil Code Section 2782 limits risk-shifting for a property owner's \"active negligence\" in construction contexts. Confirm that the agreement's indemnity and AI requirements are consistent with these limitations.\n\nIn Florida, Fla. Stat. \u00a7 627.4137 provides certain rights for claimants to receive information from insurers; if a potential claim is identified, ensure the client is aware of the right to request a certified copy of the relevant policy.\n\nIf the user identifies the governing law state in the Access Agreement, the LLM should incorporate that into the analysis, propose a short list of jurisdiction-specific verification questions (such as whether the state restricts AI for sole negligence or limits contractual indemnity scope), and explicitly flag any state-law statements for attorney verification unless the LLM has performed contemporaneous web research and can provide URLs for the authority.\n\nFor all jurisdictions, do not assert universal rules about the legal effect of certificates, enforceability of primary and non-contributory clauses, or scope of anti-indemnity statutes. Instead, treat the agreement's requirement as the commercial benchmark, flag statutory or common-law limitations as issues requiring local confirmation, and direct the supervising attorney to verify enforceability before finalizing any compliance determination that turns on state-specific law.",
